SOME NOTIONS on a MESH of a VOLUME:
===================================

The mesh of a VOLUME is a set of FE,  TETRAHEDRA et/ou
PENTAHEDRA et/ou HEXAHEDRA stockes dans 2 TMS a___xyzsommet  et  a___nsef,
defined by:

- NBSOM vertices of coordinates (Xi,Yi,Zi) in the a___xyzsommet TMS
- the array of 8 vertex numbers (NS1, NS2, ... , NS8) (1<=NS<=NBSOM)
with  NS7=NS8=0 for a PENTAHEDRON,
with  NS5=NS6=NS7=NS8=0 for a TETRAHEDRON
of NBEFOB 3D FE.

Even if the TMS structures support the storage of tangents for 3D FE,
the absence of an interpolation C1-CONTINUE with respect to
theirs faces of Clough and Tocher or 
Fraeijs de Veubeke and Sander, the mesh algorithmswill not store
the edge tangents.
For all volumes, the FE will have STRAIGHT EDGES.

                                            *V6
                                        .   |   .               V8*......*V7
                                     .      |       .            .         .
          *V3  --------*V3       V4*........|.........*V5    V5*............*V6          
         .    .     .  |           |        |         |        |            |
        .        .     |           |        *V3       |        |            |
       .      .    .   |           |    .        .    |        |V4*......*V3|
      .   .           .|           |  .             . |        |.          .|
   V1*..................*V2      V1*..................*V2    V1*............*V2
  a straight tetrahedron         a straight pentahedron   a straight hexahedron droit
     (P1 interpolation)             (R1 interpolation)       (Q1 interpolation)

In fact, if a TETRAHEDRON is subdivided in M**3 tetrahedra,
or if a  PENTAHEDRON is subdivided in MxMxN pentahedra,
or if an HEXAHEDRON  is subdivided in MxNxP hexahedra,
it is sufficient to store these 1 or 2 or 3 integers to obtain
an implicit numbering of vertices.
In this case, the mesh is said STRUCTURED,
else, it is said UNSTRUCTURED.

The quality of FE DEPENDS of quality of boundary triangles or quadrangles
because these FE will be on the boundary of volume mesh.
=> A REGULAR augmentation or diminution of the lengths of edges is necessary!

In fact, if a TETRAHEDRON is subdivided into M**3 tetrahedra,
or if a PENTAHEDRON is subdivided into MxMxN pentahedra,
or if an HEXAHEDRON is subdivided into MxMxP hexahedra,
it is sufficient to store the values of M (eventually N, P) 
to compute the number NBSOM of vertices and use an implicit 
numbering for the 8 vertices of the FE i.
In this case, the mesh is said STRUCTURED,
else, it is said UNSTRUCTURED.

Attention:
To obtain unstructured meshes as for tetrahedrization, the
User's function TAILLE_IDEALE(x,y,z) MAY BE GIVEN!
The mesh algorithms compute the edges to satisfy the
edge length, result of the call of TAILLE_IDEALE(x,y,z).
The presence of this function is sufficient to its using.

At contrary, for STRUCTURED MESHES as STRUCTURED TRIANGLE or
STRUCTURED QUADRANGLE, the call of TAILLE_IDEALE(x,y,z) is not
done because the mesh algorithm is not compatible with!

Example for the input of Taille_Ideale:
DefVar lxf,lh2,lh3;
lh2=0.3;
lh3=0.7;
lxf=max(lh2,lh3);

DefFunc Taille_Ideale(x,y,z);
  Taille_Ideale=0.45;
  If x<lxf and y>-(lh3+lh2)*1.2
    Then Taille_Ideale=0.15;
  Else
    If x<lxf and y>-(lh3+lh2)*1.8
    Then Taille_Ideale=0.28;
    EndIf;
  EndIf;
EndFunc;
Here, upper or lower cases are not signifient.


A VOLUME MAY BE CONSTRUCTED BY THE FOLLOWING OPTIONS:

1 : STRUCTURED TRANSFINITE HEXAHEDRON
The deformed HEXAEDRON is defined from its 6 meshed quadrangular faces.
Each of faces must be a STRUCTURED QUADRANGLE with respect of
the number of edges on the 3x4 common edges of the hexahedron.
A TRANSFINITE INTERPOLATION of degree 1 (COOK, GORDON, HALL method) 
maps an hexaedrisation of the unit cube onto the hexahedron with respect
to the quadrangulation of its 6 faces.
ATTENTION: The edge number of 4 parallel edges must be the same
Exemple: V1_HEXAEDRON; I; 1; QUADRANGLE1; QUADRANGLE2;QUADRANGLE3;
QUADRANGLE4; QUADRANGLE5; QUADRANGLE6;
ATTENTION: With a large deformation of the hexahedron some FE may overlap!
This overlapping is not detected!
Draw the resulting mesh to verify if the mesh is correct or not.
This overlapping problem is solved with the option 2.

2 : STRUCTURED ELLIPTICAL HEXAHEDRON
The deformed HEXAEDRON is defined from its 6 meshed quadrangular faces.
Each of faces must be a STRUCTURED QUADRANGLE with respect of
the number of edges on the 3x4 common edges of the hexahedron.
The SOLUTION of a NOT LINEAR ELLIPTICAL PARTIAL DIFFERENTIAL EQUATION
SYSTEM (WINSLOW's method+corrections) maps the UNIT CUBE onto
the HEXAHEDRON with boundary the 6 INITIAL FACES.
ATTENTION: The edge number of 4 parallel edges must be the same
ATTENTION: The overlapping of some internal hexahedra is corrected
by CONTROL FUNCTIONS located on the boundary and extended at the interior
It is possible to give
- the maximum number of iterations to correct the mesh
- a factor FADI3D (one by face) to indicate what it is prefered near
  the boundary
This value is the heigth of normal edges of nearest sub-hexahedra.
Their input must be in the same order as the 6 surfaces)

. After a pure Winslow method, these values are used to improve,
to control the orthogonality and lengths of the closed sub-hexaedra.

. The value fadi2d in ]0,1]  define the quotient height/length of edges
near the edges of the curved quadrangles:
 For example a value=1.  gives "squares"
             a value=0.1 gives a sub-quadrangle ten times large than height.

          d computed = fadi3d * (d1+d2+d3+d4)/4

                       d ?/                     
                   d1  | /d4                      
              --*------*-----*-- 
                   d3 /  d2

 By convention :
   a value=0.  => NO indication on lengths of edges
                  The angles will be improved with no other data.
   a value=-1  => Distances are conserved during the improvement of angles.
   a value=-2  => The distance d is the interpolation from d1 d2 d3 d4
                  on the boundary of this edge

       d interpolated function from d1 d2 d3 d4
                          *
                          | d4
                          *
       *                  /
    d1 |          <--- d ?/ --->          *
       |               |/                 | d2
       *---*----*------*-----*----*---*---*
                   *  /
                   | /
                d3 |/
                   *
In all cases, the angles of edges are improved.

Example: V2_HEXAHEDRON; I; 2;
QUADRANGLE1; QUADRANGLE2;QUADRANGLE3;
QUADRANGLE4; QUADRANGLE5;QUADRANGLE6; {6 quadrangular faces}
8;  0.1; 1; 2; 0; 0; 0; 
Define an hexaedrisation of contour the 6 quadrangles
with hexahedra 10 times less height than large and long 
near QUADRANGLE1, cubic hexahedra near QUADRANGLE2
2 times more height than large and long near QUADRANGLE3 and
without improvement of lengths near the 3 last QUADRANGLEs
(but, with improvements of angles to 90 degrees).

REMARQUE: Generally, the ELLIPTIC HEXAHEDRISATION is MORE ORTHOGONAL
than the TRANSFINITE HEXAHEDRISATION but the cost is more elevated!
For a RECTANGULAR PARALLELIPIPEDE of regular meshes, use the option 1
which is cheaper and produces, in this case, rectangle parallelipipedes.

3 : STRUCTURED TRANSFINITE TETRAHEDRON
The tetrahedron is defined by its 4 TRIANGULAR FACES with a 
STRUCTURED MESH.
The triangle number (>0) must be the same for any face.
ATTENTION: With a large deformation of the hexahedron some FE may overlap!
This overlapping is not detected!
Draw the resulting mesh to verify if the mesh is correct or not.
Example:   SV3_TETRAHEDRON; I; 3;
TRIANGLE1; TRIANGLE2; TRIANGLE3; TRIANGLE4; {the 4 FACES}
The tetrahedrization respects the vertices, edges and triangles of
the 6 triangular faces.

4 : STRUCTURED TRANSFINITE PENTAHEDRON
the pentahedron is defined by its 2 STRUCTURED MESH TRIANGULAR FACES
and its 3 STRUCTURED MESH QUADRANGULAR FACES.
The number of triangles(>0) must be the same on the 2 triangular faces.
The number of quadrangles(>0) in the third direction must be the same 
on the 3 quadrangular faces.
Example:   SV3_PENTAHEDRON; I; 4;
TRIANGLE1; TRIANGLE2; QUADRANGLE1; QUADRANGLE2; QUADRANGLE3;
The pentahedrization respects the vertices, edges, triangles and
quadrangles of the 5 faces.

8 : 1 CLOSED VOLUME FOR THE OPTION 9
A closed volume is used to define a material
which can be tetrahedrized with the option 9.
This volume is used to define the materials meshed after with option 9
This volume 8 is defined by the closed triangulations, boundary
of the volume 8. 
CLOSED <=> an edge belongs to 2 and only 2 triangles on the boundary.
A HOLE is also possible to retire a part of material and is furnished
as a CLOSED surface.
This option does not generate directly a mesh. The option 9 will do it!

9 : TETRAHEDRIZATION OF VOLUMES OF TYPE 8
The volume, union of all the given closed volumes of type 8
will be TETRAHEDRIZED
A list of INTERNAL POINTS, future vertices of tetrahedra
and a list of wished vertex distances around these vertices may be given.
If the user's function TAILLE_IDEALE(x,y,z) exists, it is used
to define the edge lengths of tetrahedra.

Example:
boule8;  i; 8; {the BALL defined as option 8}
1; {NBSF1V 'nombre de surfaces fermees contour du volume}
surface_trian_boule; {La SURFACE FERMEE TRIANGULEE}

boule9; i; 9; { union of closed volumes of type 8 }
10000;  { MXSOVO maximum of tetrahedrization vertices }
1.5;    { ARETGR max length of edges of the regular grid }
1;      { NBPTIV user's internal point number }
1;      { NBVOPA number of volumes of type 8 of the partition}
boule8; { name of volume option 8 }
centre; { name internal point }
0.35;   { wished edge length around point centre }
Define a tetrahedrization of a boule with edge lengths 0.35 around
the point centre

