14: SLICES FROM A GENERIC SURFACE (EXTRUSION)
The GENERATRIC SURFACE is DISPLACED N times to create N slices.
The M generic surface triangle or quadrangle define NxM pentahedra
or hexahedra.
ATTENTION: these QUADRANGLES must NOT degenerate into
TRIANGLES or EDGES or POINTS.
The last displaced surface may be the first surface to form a torus.

The DISPLACEMENT of the GENERIC SURFACE may be defined by 7 options:

0: 3 points for each slice to define the displacements
From the generic surface is associated an orthonormal reference
system E0 defined by 3 points P01 P02 P03
.P01 is the origin
.P01-P02 define the first  vector E1
.P01-P03 define the second vector E2, thus
 E3 = E1 PRODUIT VECTORIEL E2
 E2 = E3 PRODUIT VECTORIEL E1
Norm(E1)=Norm(E2)=Norm(E3)=1
Each displacement I is defined by 3 points which define
a reference system EI as above.
The DISPLACEMENT of the GENERIC SURFACE is the MAPPING from E0 to Ei
The vertices from 2 consecutive surfaces are joined to define
pentahedra and/or hexahedra
Example: V14.0; I; 14; GENERIC_SURFACE; 0; 2; {slide number}
         P01;P02;P03;  P11;P12;P13;   P21;P22;P23;
         {the 3 definition points of reference systems}

1: 3 line vertices to define the mappings of the generic surface
The reference sytems EI are defined as above with the I vertices
of the 3 lines.
E0 is defined by the first vertex of line 1 2 3
Ei is defined by the i-th  vertex of line 1 2 3 ...
Example: V14.1; I; 14; GENERIC_SURFACE; 1; L1; L2; L3;
        {the 3 lines of vertices definig the reference systems
         and the displacements of the generic surface}

2: translation of a constant cote z>0 (a stack)
The generic surface is translated of a constant cote Z>0 (stack)
Example: V14.2; I; 14; GENERIC_SURFACE; 2; 3; {slices}
         6; {cote maximum to cut into 3 slices of thickness Z=2}

3: translation of a cote z>0 for each displacement
The generic surface is translated of a variable cote z>0 input
for each displacement
ATTENTION: This is an ABSOLUTE cote Z, NOT a RELATIVE cote
to the previous displacement
Example: V14.3; I; 14; GENERIC_SURFACE; 3; 2; {slices}
         4; 7; {absolute cote Z displacement of 2 slices}

4: translation vector (x y z) valuable for all slices
The previous line is translated of a CONSTANT VECTOR (NOT NULL!)
Example: V14.4; I; 14; GENERIC_SURFACE; 4; 5; {slices}
         1; 2; 3; {the 3 constant components of translation vector}

5: translation vectors (x y z) defined one by slice
The previous line is translated of a NON CONSTANT VECTOR,
ONE by slice.
Example: V14.5; I; 14; GENERIC_SURFACE; 5; 2; {slices}
1; 2; 3; {first translation of the generic surface}
1; 2; 5; {translation of the previous surface.  Translations add}

6: 3 functions X Y Z(no_slice,x,y,z) displace the generic surface
The vertices of the generic surface are mapped by these 3 functions
from R3 to R3.
For example: ABSCISSE(no_slice,x,y,z)
             ORDINATE(no_slice,x,y,z)
             COTE    (no_slice,x,y,z)
Each vertex (x,y,z) of the generic surface becomes the vertex 
of coordinates
(ABSCISSE(no_slice,x,y,z), ORDINATE(no_slice,x,y,z),
 COTE    (no_slice,x,y,z) )  of the no_slice-th line
Example: 
DefFunc ABSCISSE(no_slice,x,y,z); ABSCISSE=no_slice*x; EndFunc;
DefFunc ORDINATE(no_slice,x,y,z); ORDINATE=no_slice*y; EndFunc;
DefFunc COTE(    no_slice,x,y,z); COTE    =no_slice*z; EndFunc;
V14.6; I; 14; GENERIC_SURFACE; 6; 5; {slices}
ABSCISSE; ORDINATE; COTE; {the 3 function names}

15: ROTATION OF A GENERIC SURFACE AROUND AN AXIS (0 TRIANGLE VERTEX on AXIS)
The generic surface is rotated N times to create N slices.
If no vertex of a triangle is on the axis, the triangle becomes a pentahedron
else, if 2 vertices of a triangle are on the axis, the triangle 
      becomes a tetrahedron
else, if 1 vertex of a triangle is on the axis,
the triangle becomes by rotation a prism which IS NOT a Mefisto FE!
(and option V31 must be used before the creation of an object)
If no vertex of a quadrangle is on the axis, the quadrangle becomes
   an hexahedron
else, the quadrangle becomes a pentahedron (which is a Mefisto FE)
The total rotation angle<=360 degrees.
Examples: 
V15.0; I; 15; GENERIC_SURFACE; P1_AXIS; P2_AXIS; 36; {rotations}
0; {constant angles} 10; {degrees} 
Define a volume by 36 rotations of 10 degrees of FE of GENERIC_SURFACE
    
V15.1; I; 15; GENERIC_SURFACE; P1_AXIS; P2_AXIS; 4; {rotations}
1; {1 angle for each rotation}
20; 30; 40; 50;
{the rotations added to obtain finally 140 degrees}
Define a volume by 4 rotations of 20 thus 50 thus 90
thus 140 degrees of the generic surface around the axis defined
points P1_AXIS and P2_AXIS

16: MAGNIFYING or EXTRUSING AN ORIENTABLE SURFACE 3D INTO LAYERS
In the normal direction to faces, triangles or quadrangles, a 
PENTA-HEXAEDRISATION of NBCOLA(>0)layers is done around.
All of layers have a small thickness EPCOLA to represent boundary layers
Then, NBLACO other layers are penta-hexhedrized with a thickness which
varies linearly from EPCOLA to EPLACO.
Attention: If the normals cross each others, the quadrangulation may
be INCORRECT!... and the penta-hexaedrisation must be restricted in
a vicinity of the line.
If one of the thicknesses is negative, the 2 thicknesses are imposed
negative and the layers are made on the other side of the initial surface

21: 1/1 CYLINDER
22: 1/2 CYLINDER  
The CYLINDER is based on the plane Z=0 and centred at ORIGIN.
The SUPERIOR PLANE is defined by the COTE Z of a POINT. 
In these 2 planes, the radius of circle must be given.
The edge lengths may used a geometrical ratio or not.
Example: CYLINDER_V21; I; 21; 
10;{edges on the cylinder radius}
3; {inferior circle radius}
1; {geometrical ratio centre -> exterior => constant edge length} 
POINT_CENTRE_SUPERIEUR; {to define the superior plane}
5; {edges on the height of cylinder}
1; {geometrical ratio Origine->centre->exterior => constant edge length}
4; {radius of cylinder in the superior plane}
24;{number of angular sectors}
1; {number of angular sectors =>constant edge length}

23: 1/1 CONE
24: 1/2 CONE  
The CONE is centred at the ORIGIN and is based in the plane Z=0.
The VERTEX of the CONE is defined by a POINT of COTE Z>0.
The edge lengths may used a geometrical ratio or not.
The number of edges on the circle arc must be EVEN.
Example: CONE_V23; I; 23; 
10; {number of edges on the radius}
2; {number of edges on the radius}
1;  {geometrical ratio centre->exterior => edge constant length}
VERTEX_CONE; {name of the point vertex of the cone (Z>0)}
8;  {number of edges on the height of the cone}
1;  {geometrical ratio base->vertex => edge constant length}
18; {EVEN number of cone angular sectors}
1;  {geometrical ratio X -> -X => edge constant length}

30: QUALITY IMPROVEMENT OF A TETRAHEDRIZATION
The tetrahedron QUALITY measures its distance to a regular tetrahedron
For a TETRAHEDRON the QUALITY = c * r /R where
r is the inscribed     radius circle of the tetrahedron
R is the circumscribed radius circle of the tetrahedron
c is a coefficient to have 1 for the regular tetrahedron.
Its value is between 0 (degenerated FE) and 1 (regular FE).

The tetrahedra with bad qualities are modified, either directly,
or with the using of vertices in the vicinity.

3 inputs to give:
- the quality under which the tetrahedron must be improved
- the coplanearity angle in degrees of 2 triangles to suppose
  they are in a same plane and may be modified
- the iteration number to do
Example: TETRA_BETTER; I; 30; INITIAL_TETRA;
 0.1;  {minimum wished quality}
   3;  {<=3 degrees, 2 faces with a common edge are in a same plane}
  10;  {iterations to do}

31: TETRAHEDRIZATION OF AN HEXA-PENTAHEDRIZATION
Each FE of the initial volume mesh is subdivided into tetrahedra.
Example: TETRAHEDRIZATION_V31; I; HEXA_PENTAHEDRISATION; 

33: HEXAHEDRIZATION of a CUBE or a SPHERE
A KERNEL is subdivided into CUBSPN**3 cubes with an edge length of
CUBSPL/CUBSPN where CUBSPL is the length of the kernel.
CUBSPD is the total length of the kernel+layers formed from
the boundary of the kernel.
With the option SPHERE, the vertices of hexahedra are projected on
co-centric spheres of radii multiples of CUBSPL/CUBSPN,
after, in geometric ratio to pass from CUBSPL/CUBSPN to the last radius
Example:
 cube3; i; 33; { HEXAHEDRIZATION of a SPHERE }
  2;  {SPHERE }
  3;  {CUBSPN number of edges in a direction of kernel}
  4;  {CUBSPC number of homothetic layers}
  3;  {CUBSPL length of cube or sphere kernel}
  10; {CUBSPD total length of the cube or sphere}
Construct an hexahedrization of a sphere of 3*3*3=27 hexahedra
+ 6*9 hexahedra for each of 4 layers.

35: EXTRACT AN HEXAHEDRON OF A STRUCTURED HEXAEDRON
Extract of a volume the hexahedra defined by 3 intervals
of edge indexes I J K of the structured hexahedron
Example: V35; I; 35; STRUCTURED_HEXA; 2;5; 4;8;  1;1;
Extract the hexahedra of edge 2 to edge 5 in I-direction, 
edge 4 to edge 8 in J-direction and edge 1 in K-direction.
                                  
36: EXTRACT A VOLUME FROM A VOLUME & CRITERION
Any tetrahedron or pentahedron or hexahedron with all their
vertices giving true for the logical User's function belongs
to the extracted volume.
Example: V36; I; 36; INITIAL_VOLUME;
deffunc PLANE_X_POSITIF(x,y,z); 
  PLANE_X_POSITIF = (x>=-0.00001);
endfunc;
PLANE_X_POSITIF;
extract the tetrahedra or pentahedra or hexahedra 
with all vertices which have an abscisse >= -0.00001
(for troncature errors)

39: SUBDIVISION of 3d FE into 8 sub-FE
Any FE of the initial volume is cut into
1 tetrahedron => 8 sub-tetrahedra
1 pentahedron => 8 sub-pentahedra
1 hexahedron  => 8 sub-hexahedra
1 pyramid     => 6 sub-pyramids and 4 tetrahedra
(and option V31 must be used before the creation of an object)
Example: V39; I; 39; INITIAL_VOLUME;
  
48: IMPOSED POINTS ONTO the NEAREST VERTEX of the VOLUME
The 3 coordinates of the nearest vertex to a named point
are replaced by the 3 coordinates of the point.
Attention, the quality of finite elements may be modified.

50: MAPPING OF A VOLUME
An existing volume is transformed by a predefined MAPPING
Example: V50; PLANE_SYMMETRY; 50; INITIAL_VOLUME;
The vertices of the VOLUME V50 are the images of vertices
of INITIAL_VOLUME by the mapping PLANE_SYMMETRY

51: UNION OF SEVERAL VOLUMES
The resulting volume will be an UNION of volumes grouped
under a unique name.
An UNION of volumes is handled after as any other volume
The common vertices of 2 volumes are identified
to form an unique vertex. If this identification is NOT
correct, modify the identification precision EPZERO and EPSXYZ
of vertices by the option 20 of the Debut menu.
Example: V51; I; 51;   5; V1;V2;V3;V4;V5;

53: 1 MULTI-MATERIAL VOLUME (union of different volumes)
GIVES MANY MONO-MATERIAL VOLUMES

54: 1 MULTI-MATERIAL VOLUME (union of different volumes)
GIVES ONLY ONE MONO-MATERIAL VOLUME

61 : REGULAR 6-CUBE OF TYPE FINITE DIFFERENCES
In R6, a 6-CUBE [a,b]**6 is meshed with 6-cubes [x,x+h]**6
of FINITE DIFFERENCE type.
(orthogonal parallelipipeds generalized in dimension 6)

ATTENTION:
A 6-cube => 2**6 C06 0-cubes =  64 vertices
         => 2**5 C16 1-cubes = 192 edges
         => 2**4 C26 2-cubes = 240 2-cubes
         => 2**3 C36 3-cubes = 160 3-cubes
         => 2**2 C46 4-cubes =  60 4-cubes
         => 2**1 C56 5-cubes =  12 faces 5-cubes

The ORIGIN of AXISES is
either the centre of the 6-cube,
or     the minimum of its coordinates.
The constant number of edges in a direction is required.
The value h, edge length, are required.

62 : SIMILARITY OF 6-CUBES
The 6-cube mesh is formed of a central kernel 6-cube.
Each of its 12 faces (5-cubes) creates by central similarity
N levels of 12 6-cubes
The width of the kernel 6-cube is required.
The number N of levels is required.

63 : 3 FINITE DIFFERENCES AND SIMILARITY OF 6-CUBES
The mesh is formed of a kernel of 3**6 6-cubes of
finite difference type  (as option 61) and N levels of
similarity of the kernel faces to produce 6-cubes.
The width of the kernel 6-cube is required.
The total width of the 6-cube is required.
The number N of levels is required.


81: RENAME THE VOLUME
ATTENTION TO THE ORDER OF INPUT!
Example: NEW_NAME; I; 81; OLD_NAME;
Rename the surface OLD_NAME into NEW_NAME

82: DELETE THE VOLUME
Delete the volume from the input of its name done previously
Example: V82; I; 82;   delete the volume V82 if it existed
